00:04:02.780 --> 00:04:06.860
theology, he came across an interesting
book called, "Le Phénomène Humain, " that

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:11.920
was written by a Jesuit paleontologist,
Pierre de Chardin. And of course, "Le

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:17.340
Phénomène Humain" is "The Phenomenon of
Man, " and it is what CARTA is striving to

00:04:17.340 --> 00:04:24.800
explain. What is it that makes us this
very strange ape, among other apes, but

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:31.220
with our very, very special attributes
that will be discussed today. Reading “Le

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:35.840
Phénomène Humain” sparked his interest in
Evolution and Genetics. And so, he

00:04:35.840 --> 00:04:39.630
actually came to Columbia University, he
was very fortunate to have some advisors

00:04:39.630 --> 00:04:43.880
in Spain that knew Theodosius Dobzhansky,
one of the major architects of the Modern

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:49.400
Synthesis of Evolution, who was a
geneticist interested in actually

00:04:49.400 --> 00:04:54.780
observing and empirically measuring what
was going on in natural populations of

00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:59.840
organisms that are busy evolving. And of
course, the work horse of naturally

00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:07.910
evolving organisms was Drosophila. So long
before the advent of isozymes or

00:05:07.910 --> 00:05:12.890
restriction enzymes or DNA sequence,
geneticist were very busy observing

00:05:12.890 --> 00:05:16.760
generations after generations of these
tiny, little fruit-flies that annoy you,

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:21.990
around your bananas near your kitchen. And
selecting for new phenotypes and wondering

00:05:21.990 --> 00:05:26.460
what it is. They could see the chromosomes
but they couldn't read the DNA yet. Once

00:05:26.460 --> 00:05:30.910
there were restriction enzymes, they could
start cutting the DNA at specified places,

00:05:30.910 --> 00:05:36.020
still not being able to read the actual
sequence. So, years of years of study, a

00:05:36.020 --> 00:05:41.900
PhD on the genetics of Drosophila
continued, lead professor Ayala to look at

00:05:41.900 --> 00:05:46.900
a variety of other organisms, and then
with the aid of more modern techniques.

00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:52.540
Among these organisms, featured some very
prominent protozoans, like Trypanosomes,

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:57.330
in this case T.cruzi from South America
that causes Chagas disease that might be

00:05:57.330 --> 00:06:03.130
one of the things that ail Darwin for so
long. It turns out, these organisms are

00:06:03.130 --> 00:06:07.870
diploid, but they're mostly asexual. So,
here you have organisms with a lot of

00:06:07.870 --> 00:06:13.530
variability that forgo sex for most of the
part. And it turns out, all these

00:06:13.530 --> 00:06:21.270
organisms are parasitic. So, contributions
to the biology of these Trypanosomes

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:27.720
continued. So did contributions to this
major disease-causing organism, in this

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:31.820
case a merozoites of a Plasmodium
falciparum, the major disease of our

00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:38.950
species. And by now, with help of
sequence...full on genome sequencing, it

00:06:38.950 --> 00:06:43.040
was possible to actually retrace the
history of organisms, such as these

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:47.390
protozoa, that have been plaguing
human-kind for a very long time. And even

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:53.790
reconstruct the evolutionary history that
jumps between species. But, of course, the

00:06:53.790 --> 00:06:57.800
fact that the book, one of the things that
sparked Francisco Ayala's interest in

00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:03.170
evolution and genetics was The Human
Phenomenon makes him a card-carrying

00:07:03.170 --> 00:07:09.150
anthropogenist, in terms of trying to
understand what it is that makes us such a

00:07:09.150 --> 00:07:15.000
bizarre paradoxical ape. And I thought,
given today's topic, I would not end

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:21.620
before reading a short chapter out of
Dobzhansky's book called, "Mankind

00:07:21.620 --> 00:07:25.800
Evolving, " from 1962, published a year
before I was born, and this is out of the

00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:32.670
library of my late father, in which
Dobzhansky makes a very important thesis,

00:07:32.670 --> 00:07:37.810
namely that "Human evolution has two
components: the biological, or organic;

00:07:37.810 --> 00:07:43.110
and the cultural, or super-organic. These
components are neither mutually exclusive,

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:49.040
nor independent, but interrelated and
interdependent. Human evolution cannot be

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:54.580
understood as a purely biological process,
nor can it be adequately described as a

00:07:54.580 --> 00:08:00.280
history of culture. It is the interaction
of biology and culture. There exists a

00:08:00.280 --> 00:08:08.200
feedback between biological and cultural
processes." So, we'll have the pleasure to

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:13.210
hear professor Ayala talk about ethics and
morality today. And, of course, he is a

00:08:13.210 --> 00:08:18.300
very well-know Evolutionary Biologist. He
has been called, rightly, the "Renaissance

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:22.630
Man of Evolutionary Biology, " and is a
recipient of many, many prestigious

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:26.220
honors, including the National Medal of
Science; he's a member of National Academy

00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:33.800
of Science of the United States, of
Mexico, the Collège de France, Russia, and

00:08:33.800 --> 00:08:43.410
Serbia and that's just a very small list
of the many declarations that he has been

00:08:43.410 --> 00:08:49.520
given. So, without farther ado, let me
introduce Francisco Ayala on "Evolution of

00:08:49.520 --> 00:08:59.120
Ethical Behavior and Moral Values:
Biology? Culture?"

